description.text:
This is printed without supports on a large printer like the Big Builder Dual Extruder. You can scale it down by lowering the heigth scale to our maximum printable size. The lamp hole has to be on the top and printed as the latest part.
In the design all items are calculated to be able to be printed without supports respecting the 45 degrees angle limit as much as possible.
I printed this lamp with http://colorfabb.com/orange-translucent in a gradient to http://colorfabb.com/red-transparent which gives it a hip look with retro elements.
It took a lot of hours to get the right effect and make layers. The inside holes show as an effect when the light is on.

This is my contribution to the builder community. Thank you for all your shares. If you want super cool nice laser sintered nylon spectacles with or without prescription lenses or have a commercial interest. Please mail me at [email protected]

description.text:
The mendel-parts.com V9 1,75mm Hotend/Extruder works reliable with PLA.
Unfortunately 1,75mm ABS filament is softer and more flexible, which can cause some problems.
Sometimes the filament bends before entering the hotend tube and curls up between filament drive and hotend.
This upgrade solves that problem.

1) Configure clearance and hight parameter in scad file, if necessary.
2) Print
3) Drill out holes:
Middle hole: 5.9mm - 6.0mm
Filament hole: 2.0mm
Side 4.0mm - 4.5mm
4) Disassemble Extruder and attach printed part (see photo)
5) Reassemble extruder, make sure, that the side screws can move freely
6) Make sure, that the filament drive can move freely and has enough clearance
7) Post a comment if you have suggestions

title: Iron Man Arc Reactor for Osram Dot-it LED

description.text:
I scaled the original to fit these cheap LED lamps.

1: Remove the silver front cover by cutting along between the cover and the plastic base, cutting the glue and forcing the cover off.

2: Cut off the soldering between two of the battery compartments.

3: Remove the battery cover and batteries and jam two pieces of uninsolated wire behind the battery contacts. Once you put the batteries back in and the battery cover on, they will stay quite well. Now the LEDs will switch on when you connect the wires, just make sure the switch in the center is on.

4: Put the arc reactor on along with a cover you either print in transparent filament or cut from something. I hot glued the reactor and cover together and stuck it on the base with double-sided tape for easy removal.

I leave to you to figure out your prefered switch mechanism. I just had the old light switch lying around so I soldered it onto the wires.

As for sticking to your clothes, the lamps I bought came with some mounting accesories; some sticky material, some magnetic sheet and piece of magnetic metal with a ring for putting it on a hook. I hotglued some magnet to the battery cover and stuck them to the metal piece through my t-shirt.

description.text:
I made an enclosure for my Wanhao Duplicator i3 v2 from an Ikea cupboard. I got the instructions here.

I mounted the spool holder on top and drilled a hole to feed the filmant through. The thing is that the cupboard is not made from solid wood, but rather thin sheets and honeycomb which you are gonna feel whenever you are feeding filament through. Just print the tube and jam it in the hole for easy feeding.

Do NOT drill the hole directly over the printhead as it will have the filament rub against the top of the frame. I tried and I am not ashamed enough to edit it out of the pictures. Rather drill a bit in front of the printhead.

As for the rest of the enclosure for those curious: The printer is standing a few sheets of cardboard glued together with some "planks" on the bottom cut from the packing foam the printer came in. This absorps a lot of vibrations making the printer much more quiet since vibration does not carry out through your apartment. If you get a 2m LED strip it will fit the top of the cupboard perfectly and you can feed the wire through the mounting hole on the back.

UPDATE 12/8/2016: If you want spool holders, grab yourself some Capita legs while at Ikea. The model on the picture holds two spool per leg.

UPDATE 30/12/2016: The cupboard is not build to stand on a table with the heave door on it and it will start slanting. You can fix this by putting screws in diagonal corners and tighten some string between them to keep it study. You can do this cheaply using some nuts and bolts like on the picture.

Printed plotter!

YouTube link: https://youtu.be/1TkYPDmsMEE

I always liked to build a 2D-Plotter, finally i'm done and i really want to share it to everyone.

In the future i will add:

  • dremel holder
  • laser holder
  • a new project to scan pictures

This project learned me to make a todo-list and how to start a project. I started this project in a technic lesson, my teacher
Said he never had seen a boy of age 13 doing this before!

Thanks to Makeblock for their penlift and arduino code

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

30%

Printing...... Extra info

The plotter is based on a arduino uno, the .ino code is from makeblock. You only have to change the arduino pin numbers.

Step 1

I started design in Tinkercad, i had the idea already and created it in 3d.

Step 2

I splitted the parts into printable objects and printed it with the 3D-Printer

Step 3

put it all together, with nuts and screws, tayrib and other stuff.

Step 4

Installed all the steppers and the servo and wired them, then i started programming in the Arduino IDE.

Step 5

I ws solving issues like wrong wiring.

Step 6

I'm done!
it is inspired by a real CNC machine
Look at lessons/activities! ^^^^^^

  • 3x Unipolar Steppers

  • Arduino Mega + ramps 1.4

  • Stepper wires
  • a 3D printer of course or look at http://www.3d-technics.jimdo.com/get-printed for cheap and high quality printing!
  • ball bearings
  • Remembver to use a easy to use construction, i used Flamco rail: http://flamco.nl

Overview

When you start this project you learn how make a plan (todo-list). You also learn how to program with the arduino.

objectives

You should learn:

  • creating a plan
  • make a todo-lost
  • programming with the arduino
  • using a 3d-printer
audiences

Skills:

  • a bit of engineering and science
subjects

Science, math, technic

skills learned

When you finished this project hou should be better in:

  • programming hardware (arduino)
  • using a 3d-printer
lessons/activity

The first lessons you start with making a plan.

Lesson 3/4/5/6:
Start 3d-printing the parts .

Lesson 6/7/8:
use screws and nuts to build the base for the plotter.

Lesson 8/9/10/11:
Install all the hardware to the arduino and make sure the steppers are not in 5V but on a 12V circuit.

Lesson 11/12:
Download the makeblock code and find out how to upload the code to the arduino.

FINISHED!

~2 months

title: Adapter from Dyson vacuums to 1-1/4 inch shop vac hoses and accessories

description.text: On thing about the wonderful line of Dyson DC vacuums is that nothing fits their hoses or brushes except their own parts.  They are ingenious, but sometimes you'd like to use that one shop vac accessory, and can't.  This adaptor will let you attach those 1-1/4 inch accessories to many of the Dyson accessories.

This adapter was made from measurement of the attachments that came with, or were bought for, our Dyson DC39 vacuum.  The tolerances on the Dyson fittings are fairly liberal, so it took two takes to get something that would fit everything.  
I would print this at 100% size (I've allowed for 2% shrinkage), and with the bottom down on a raft.  Infill of 100%, 3 shells, and no support (there is a slight overhang, but no support is needed).  Extruder temp is 240C, and the build plate is set to 115C (remember that temp readings are relative - use what works for you).  I find that 240C for the extruder with ABS causes the ABS to fuse together very well.  The resulting thing can take a lot of punishment.  I tried squeezing it to break the thinnest part, and it would not bend or crack.  
Using SimLab Composer 2014 I can convert the original SolidWorks file to several other formats, but I cannot guarantee  that they will be usable.  The SLDPRT and STL files are the only ones I know work.

description.text: I was working on couple Aerotech rocket kits and wanted to add electronics. The two kits are the Mustang and Arreaux both have 1.9" diameter tubes. The Mustang is short and does not allow a lot of space for extra stuff so that became the model to design around. The nosecones on these models are plastic and hollow which became the ideal place to add something. Holes to mount the electronics are for the Raven altimeter (v1)

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker Original

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm or more

Infill:

35%

Notes:

The STL file is one part but can be made into three (at least with Cura) if you like. Choose higher infill setting as the front plate will be glued in and has a 1/4" rod used to attach to the recovery system. There will be some hold back force here.

To start off, you will need to cut away some plastic on the nosecone shoulder, refer to the picture and just cutaway the angled section including the recovery harness attachment loop. Cut conservatively as you can trim this easier once the main part is removed and you can fit in the 3d printed hood.

You will need a 6-7" piece of 1/4" rod with threads on each end along with the nuts. I used plain aluminum rod and tapped a 1/4-20 thread on each end with the inside nosecone thread 3/4" long. and the other end for recovery attachment 1.5" long to accommodate a custom built round nut and screw eye for recovery attachment. The pictures should explain things more clearly but let me know if you need more information.

Once printed, the round but flat piece is the front disk that will be glued inside the nosecone. It fits in the shoulder section snugly but once past that and into the nose section it will move easily. Note there is a slight bevel on this piece and the smaller end should go in first matching the nose profile. (ok not really matching but it is a place that allows for a greater glue bond surface.

I found it best to add the rod with threads and nut with the front disk and use the rod to push through the shoulder section and find the sweet spot for the front disk to rest. Be careful not to push the disk in hard as it will deform the nose. Once in position mark the back of the rod with the end of the shoulder and this would be the end of the threading for the recovery side of the rod.

You will also have to notch the end of the shoulder to fit the rod down into. There is no need to have this secured as the rear hood piece should interlock with the nosecone and hold the assembly tight.

Now that the parts are test fitted, time to add some glue to make the front disk solid with the nosecone. I added tape on the front side of the front disk to stop any epoxy from dripping through, just enough to cover the square holes for the carrier. With sandpaper wrapped on a rod or something similar sand the rough up the inside of the nosecone where the front disk will be attached. This is necessary for the glue to adhere. Now mix up some 5 minute or 12 minute epoxy (~7-10 ml) and pour it into the nosecone ensuring the pour is onto the section where the front disk will sit. Don't worry that it is dripping further into the nosecone as we will invert the cone and the epoxy will run back to the disk face and sides. Now you see the reason for the tape. When inserting the front disk I foud it helpful to have the carrier piece attached to make sure the alignment is lined up with the rear shoulder part (see pics).

Not added to the STL file mounting plate was wire strain relief holes or the battery mount. That may be rev 6 of the design but for now you can just drill through where required. The SCAD file has been uploaded if you care to mess around and add some features or adjust to other nosecones.

description.text:
This is an experiment with different ways to connect multiple pieces of a model together. The model is a hollow sphere which has been split about 3/4 of the way along one axis. I then added different structures to reconnect the two pieces together. I put the male component on the larger piece of the sphere because that seemed more mechanically challenging.
One model uses a simple peg-in-socket design. Nothing but friction holds the two pieces together, and I found that a difference of 0.5mm to 1.0mm in the diameters of the pegs and sockets gave good results with the vagaries of my printer.
The other model uses a more sophisticated clip design with a half-sphere on one side, which mates to a similar socket on the cap. Here I found that a 3mm thick clip gives a good compromise between strength and flexibility.

1) Print both halves of each model.
2) Clip together. Pull apart. Repeat.

description.text:
Experimental diving rings for my daughter to use in the pool. There is an air pocket in one side, allowing the rings to rest upright at the bottom of the pool, making them easy to grab.

NOTE! This is experimental. It would obviously be easiest to print something hollow and add a weight (maybe drop it in while printing, or stick it on afterwards, but I wanted to try having it just work right out of the printer. It turns out that the margins of proper buoyancy are fairly slim when dealing with PLA, so very small differences in printer settings can make a big difference and throw off the buoyancy, causing it to "fail" by either sinking flat to the bottom or floating on the top.

There are 4 models, numbered 1-4. They go from most buoyant to least buoyant. ABS will not work without significant changes as it is very close to the density of water, making the margins very slim or even negative if there is any trapped air in the print. I wish this were more predictable, do not be surprised if you end up with a couple of rings that "fail" (float or sink flat).

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

No

No

0.15 mm layer height

Notes:

Print at 100% or you'll get unexpected bubbles throwing off the buoyancy. You may get those anyway!

Print with PLA. ABS is too light, it would need to be redesigned and the buoyancy margins would be painfully thin, much more so than PLA.

Throw it in some water: it sinks?

Does it sink to the bottom and lay flat? Try printing one of the models with a smaller number. Or try using some sandpaper or otherwise removing small amounts of material until it is buoyant enough to stand up on the bottom.

Throw it in some water: it floats?

Sorry, you need to add weight. Try re-printing a more buoyant model, or possibly change the settings to print more dense. For example printing slower sometimes results in less air getting trapped in the models, in my experience.

description.text:
A simple case which can contain the following:

-Raspberry Pi Zero 1.3: [https://www.adafruit.com/products/2885]
-Raspberry Pi Camera v2: [https://www.adafruit.com/products/3099]
-Edimax EW-7811Un 150Mbps 11n Wi-Fi USB Adapter: [https://www.amazon.com/Edimax-EW-7811Un-150Mbps-Raspberry-Supports/dp/B003MTTJOY]
-PowerBoost 1000: [https://www.adafruit.com/products/2465]
-28mmx74mmx3mm 800Ah LiPO Battery: Recycled from a broken Wahl shaver
-9mm DPDT Slide Switch: [https://www.radioshack.com/products/dpdt-6vdc-slide-switch-1]
-6mm Tactile Button Switch: [https://www.adafruit.com/products/367]

WiFi adapter was disassembled and connected to the Pi according to the very helpful guide by Chris Robinson @n-o-d-e.net: [http://n-o-d-e.net/post/138478383831/how-to-add-a-low-profile-wifi-board-to-a-raspberry]

I do not code, but I threw together the following which reads the momentary switch off of GPIO pin 4 and takes a picture. If the button is held for more than a quarter of a second, then video is taken. The video is killed at the next button press and converted into MP4 format:

http://pastebin.com/c30ivmsC

In conjunction with this script, I also created a bash script to watch for '.jpg' and '.mp4' file extensions in the home directory. If the WiFi is connected and the Pi can reach the Internet via curl, then it will go through a for loop of the present media files, upload them to Dropbox via the dropbox_uploader.sh script [https://github.com/andreafabrizi/Dropbox-Uploader/blob/master/dropbox_uploader.sh], and finally delete them once they've been uploaded to save space. If not connected to the Internet, it will just store the files locally until I'm back on the WiFi:

http://pastebin.com/UPd6SeLT

Both of these scripts were appended to list from the 'sudo cronjob -e' command in the following manner. You will need to create a 'logs' folder in the home directory to see the log files:

@reboot /usr/bin/python /home/pi/raspi-camera-button.py > /home/pi/logs/camera-cronlog 2>&1
@reboot /bin/bash /home/pi/drop-upload.sh > /home/pi/logs/dropbox-cronlog 2>&1

Howdy True Believers!

So I have been reading Thor and Marvel for close to 20 years now, and when I saw Garrett's creation (love your channel buddy!) my jaw just dropped at what he had designed! He seriously deserves a sub and a like on all of his videos if you have never checked him out

Now being who I am as a person, I felt the need to tinker just a little bit with his design. I am a member of the RPF and I love seeing people craft and wear their fandom so I decided to modify a few things here and there so I could satisfy my love of both the MCU hammer and also the design from the comics!

So here is a list of changes/upgrades I have made:

  • I scanned in a comic from my collection and using polylines traced the "Worthy" inscription straight from the pages of Jason Aaron and Russell Dauterman's Thor #1. I did however make a small change as the inscription is now Gender Neutral so both genders can cosplay with my Mjolnir no problems! Lady Thor is freaking Kickass yo!

  • I redesigned the handle so the chevrons are more prominent. This was done so I could template and use genuine Kangaroo hide to leather wrap my handle as they did with the MCU Hero Prop. If you can get your hands on it, aim for leather with a thickness of around 700gsm. Barge Glue Works wonders for this part!

  • I designed a new end cap for the handle, pre-notched and ready to accept a 40cm long, 2-2.4mm thick leather strap. And Last but not least...

  • I redesigned Garrets Stand so it can accept a data plaque made by BrotherFoster. :)

Here is my design for the stand:

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1632630

And here is the link to BrotherFosters' Etsy Store if you want a plaque of your own:

https://www.etsy.com/au/listing/177626781/thor-mjolnir-nameplate-for-your-hammer?ref=hp_rv

In terms of finishing the piece, this is my process:

1: Sand my part with 100 grit sandpaper to knock the majority of excess plastic off quickly. This takes around 10 hours per part.
2: Wet Sand with 200 grit sandpaper until the part is smooth to the touch (20-30 hours)
3: Spray with a High Fill Catalysed auto primer (to catch any areas I may have missed)
4: Repeat steps 1-3 until the part looks injection moulded.
5: Wet Sand with 320 grit sandpaper (20-30 hours) for a mirror like surface.
6: Prime the part again with a normal spray primer.
7: Apply Paint to my part.

In terms of Paint, I first laid down a gloss black (Dulux Brand) and then I took a hammered metal spray-paint (also dulux brand) and lightly misted the surface until I got the shiny Uru metallic sheen I wanted. If you want the more MCU look, skip the black and lay down hammered metal quite heavily and then finish the entire piece with a black acrylic wash once complete. :) It will make your details pop!

And that's about it! Let me tell you, just holding this thing makes you feel Worthy. ;) Happy printing!

Edit: I have had a few requests for a 'Whole' hammer for those with a larger printer. :) The parts have been uploaded under the filename "Mjolnir (Whole)" but I will leave print orientation up to you as it will be a 90 hour print at 0.3mm resolution (conservatively) with a TON of support material. You will also need to print the "Mjolnir End Cap" separately if you plan on attaching a leather loop on the end of the handle. The loop needs to be screwed down so there wasn't a lot I could do about that one... :)

description.text: This is the fish design which was created to go with the Chinese language course in our local primary school. This page will include the model/design as well as the steps I took to construct it.

This was designed in Tinkercad, which I'm sure most of you already know and/or if you have read the main project's page, you will be acquainted with it's advantages and usage scenarios.

Every design has to start with an initial idea. Mindlessly placing blocks down, waiting for something to come to you or hoping it'll turn into something great doesn't always work.
That's why research can be a key step in creating something. I generally just browse Thingiverse or Tinkercad galleries and draw in my inspiration from there.

For a class of young kids, letting them draw their ideas or plans will help them visualize it for later, this is if they will be designing it themselves. If they are going to just play around in Tinkercad and/or customize a premade model, making them draw their idea may be counter-intuitive.
Older kids such as year 5 through to high school will probably not benefit from drawing their plans but a different method of getting them to create plans will still be helpful. This could include a class discussion or talking to the children individually. Talking amongst themselves, ideally while they have access to Tinkercad is great too.

As with all models, they have to start with some basic building blocks. For this case (and in most others), it became a sphere. I then stretched it to resemble a cartoony fish.
I then went ahead and put in the tail. It was just a paraboloid, rotated 90° and stretched/shrunk. It intersects with the body in the center just about where I thought it looked good.

Note that throughout the design process, I've been keeping in mind that I would eventually 3d print it. That influenced a few of my choices regarding overhang angles.

This was the design of the dorsal fin. I had envisioned something like a dolphin's fin, and as I went through all the different shapes i could use to cut out back end, I finally decided on a slightly squished hemisphere, moving it around until it looked alright and then grouping them together. It didn't leave me with the perfect fin, but was good enough.

As seen above, I moved and re-sized the dorsal fin into it's position.
Then I created a pectoral fin. Yet again, it is another paraboloid. And again, as always it was just a task of resizing and reshaping.
However for this part of the design, since I had moved it into some absurd angles, I decided to use the mirror tool instead of manually copying and rotating it. The tool can be found under the adjust tab in the top bar. When an object is selected, it allows you reverse it over the x, y or z axis. Very helpful.

The eyes, two spheres placed at the front of the head. That's about it really.

I was looking at it after I'd done the eyes, and suddenly thought it needed a mouth. A goldfish mouth to be precise. Why? Remember when I said I was thinking about being able to print this. I couldn't make a pacman style mouth because the overhangs wouldn't work well, so a spherical hole makes much more sense.

But on a side note. Aren't goldfish so cute close up.

So you may have noticed that I've been placing some of the shapes partly under the work plane. This ties back into the printability of the model. It needs a flat surface both for adhesion and tidiness. That's why I used a square block to cut away everything underneath the work plane.

So there you have it. The finished design of a simple fish easily created in Tinkercad. This is one of the simpler designs but sure looks decent enough, even when it's printed.

description.text:
This is a simple model of a Trimaran with a sail that turns (as it is printed separately and drops into a hole in the deck). The ability to bridge the hulls is what impresses people most about this model. It looks great when the Trimaran and Sail are printed separately in different colors.

This is an easy print as long as your machine bridges well... as it needs to string the filament between the hulls to join them. The stringing will be visible on the underside but you won't see it when turned the right way up.

At standard scale the Trimaran measures approx. 97mm long and 80mm wide. The Sail's total height is approx. 130mm of which 10mm drop into the hole in the deck.

You can print the Trimaran with just two shells and 10 - 15% infill however the Sail needs to be more shells (3) and high infill (75%) to make sure the mast is strong. However, this doesn't use much filament due to the Sail being very thin.

Take care when removing the Sail from the build plate and removing the raft (if used) so you don't crack / break it. It shouldn't be too fragile but it's better to take you time than have to print it again....

Please read the print instructions and view the images for additional information.... and post photos of your Trimarans!
